  "local_port": 54438,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do we forget any Wi-Fi in Windows 10?",
  "response": "Forgetting a Wi-Fi network in Windows 10 can help resolve connectivity issues or simply remove networks you no longer use. There are several methods to achieve this, including using the **Settings** app, the **Network & Internet** settings, or the **Command Prompt**. Below are detailed steps for each method:\n\n---\n\n### **Method 1: Using the Settings App**\n\n1. **Open Settings:**\n   - Click on the **Start** button (Windows logo) located at the bottom-left corner of your screen.\n   - Select the **Settings** gear icon, or press **Windows Key + I** to open the Settings directly.\n\n2. **Navigate to Network Settings:**\n   - In the Settings window, click on **Network & Internet**.\n\n3. **Access Wi-Fi Settings:**\n   - In the left-hand menu, select **Wi-Fi**.\n\n4. **Manage Known Networks:**\n   - Click on **Manage known networks**. This will display a list of all Wi-Fi networks your computer has connected to previously.\n\n5. **Forget the Desired Network:**\n   - Find the Wi-Fi network you want to forget in the list.\n   - Click on the network's name to expand its options.\n   - Click the **Forget** button. The network will be removed from the list of known networks.\n\n   ![Manage Known Networks](https://support.microsoft.com/library/images/win10/manage_known_networks.png)  \n   *_Image for illustration purposes only._*\n\n---\n\n### **Method 2: Using the Network & Internet Settings**\n\n1. **Access Network Settings:**\n   - Right-click on the **Wi-Fi** icon in the system tray (bottom-right corner of the screen).\n   - Select **Open Network & Internet settings** from the context menu.\n\n2. **Go to Wi-Fi Settings:**\n   - In the Settings window, ensure that **Wi-Fi** is selected in the left-hand panel.\n\n3. **Manage Known Networks:**\n   - Click on **Manage known networks**.\n\n4. **Forget the Desired Network:**\n   - Locate the Wi-Fi network you wish to forget.\n   - Click on the network name to reveal more options.\n   - Click the **Forget** button to remove the network from your known networks list.\n\n---\n\n### **Method 3: Using Command Prompt**\n\nFor users comfortable with using the Command Prompt, you can forget a Wi-Fi network using the following steps:\n\n1. **Open Command Prompt as Administrator:**\n   - Press **Windows Key + X** and select **Windows PowerShell (Admin)** or **Command Prompt (Admin)** from the menu.\n   - If prompted by User Account Control (UAC), click **Yes** to allow.\n\n2. **View All Saved Wi-Fi Profiles:**\n   - Type the following command and press **Enter**:\n     ```\n     netsh wlan show profiles\n     ```\n   - This will display a list of all Wi-Fi networks your PC has connected to.\n\n3. **Forget the Desired Network:**\n   - To forget a specific network, type the following command, replacing `NetworkName` with the exact name of the Wi-Fi network you want to forget:\n     ```\n     netsh wlan delete profile name=\"NetworkName\"\n     ```\n     *Example:*\n     ```\n     netsh wlan delete profile name=\"HomeWiFi\"\n     ```\n   - Press **Enter** to execute the command. You should see a confirmation message indicating that the profile was successfully deleted.\n\n4. **Verify Deletion (Optional):**\n   - To ensure the network has been forgotten, you can run the `show profiles` command again:\n     ```\n     netsh wlan show profiles\n     ```\n   - Confirm that the desired network no longer appears in the list.\n\n---\n\n### **Additional Tips**\n\n- **Reconnecting to a Forgotten Network:**\n  - If you ever need to reconnect to a forgotten Wi-Fi network, simply select it from the list of available networks and enter the required password.\n\n- **Automatic Connection:**\n  - When reconnecting, ensure that the **Connect automatically** option is checked if you want your PC to connect to the network automatically in the future.\n\n- **Troubleshooting:**\n  - Forgetting and then reconnecting to a Wi-Fi network can often resolve common connectivity issues, especially if there have been changes to the network's settings.\n\n---\n\nBy following any of the methods above, you can easily forget a Wi-Fi network in Windows 10. Choose the method that you're most comfortable with to manage your network connections effectively.",
